    "markdown": "## MRI Knee Joint Overview\n\n### Definition & Technology Behind MRI\nMagnetic Resonance Imaging uses a powerful magnetic field and radio waves to create cross-sectional pictures of your knee. Unlike X-ray or CT, \\*\\*MRI does not use ionising radiation\\*\\*, making it ideal for soft-tissue evaluation.\n### MRI vs X-ray vs CT for the Knee\n| Feature | MRI | X-ray | CT |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Soft-tissue clarity | Excellent | Poor | Average |\n| Radiation | None | Yes | Yes |\n| Bone detail | Good | Excellent | Excellent |\n| Ideal for | Ligaments, menisci, cartilage | Fractures | Complex fractures |\n\n## Risks & Limitations of MRI Knee Joint\n\n- \\*\\*Magnetic field safety\\*\\*: Pacemakers, cochlear implants, and some aneurysm clips may be contraindicated.\n- \\*\\*Claustrophobia\\*\\*: Our wide-bore 70 cm scanner and on-demand sedation keep 97 % of patients comfortable.\n- \\*\\*Cost\\*\\*: Slightly higher than X-ray but offset by superior diagnostic accuracy.\n\n## Parameters Considered During MRI Knee Joint\n\n- \\*\\*Ligaments\\*\\*: ACL, PCL, MCL, LCL integrity\n- \\*\\*Menisci\\*\\*: Medial & lateral meniscus tears or degeneration\n- \\*\\*Cartilage thickness\\*\\*: Early arthritis detection\n- \\*\\*Bone marrow edema\\*\\*: Stress injuries & bone bruises\n\n## When to Take Test\n\n- Persistent knee pain unrelieved by rest\n- Visible swelling or locking episodes\n- Instability after twisting injury\n- Pre-surgical planning & post-op follow-up\n\n## Benefits of Taking the Test\n\n- Zero radiation exposure\n- Early detection of ligament tears & cartilage defects\n- Guides targeted physiotherapy or surgery\n- Prevents unnecessary arthroscopy\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed with MRI Knee Joint\n\n| Condition | What MRI Shows |\n|---|---|\n| \\*\\*ACL/PCL tear\\*\\* | Discontinuity & signal change |\n| \\*\\*Meniscus tear\\*\\* | Linear high signal reaching surface |\n| \\*\\*Cartilage defects\\*\\* | Thinning, fissuring, or full-thickness loss |\n| \\*\\*Osteoarthritis\\*\\* | Joint-space narrowing, osteophytes |\n| \\*\\*Bone contusions\\*\\* | Marrow edema pattern |\n\n## Preparing for MRI Knee Joint\n\n- \\*\\*Clothing\\*\\*: Wear metal-free attire; we provide hospital gowns if needed.\n- \\*\\*Metal objects\\*\\*: Remove jewellery, belts, credit cards, hearing aids.\n- \\*\\*Fasting\\*\\*: Only if contrast is planned—fast 4 hours prior.\n- \\*\\*Inform\\*\\*: Let us know about pregnancy, implants, or prior contrast reactions.\n---\n## Pre-requisites\n- Doctor’s prescription & referral (can be arranged on site)\n- Previous imaging reports (CT/X-ray) for comparison\n---\n## Best Time to Take the Test\n- \\*\\*Early slots (7–9 am)\\*\\*: Shorter wait times\n- \\*\\*Post-injury 48–72 hours\\*\\*: Ideal window after swelling plateaus\n---\n## Eligibility\n- \\*\\*Age\\*\\*: Safe for infants to seniors\n- \\*\\*Pregnancy\\*\\*: First-trimester scans deferred unless urgent; shielding provided in second & third trimesters\n---\n## Step-by-Step Procedure\n1. \\*\\*Check-in & safety screening\\*\\* – 10 minutes\n2. \\*\\*Positioning\\*\\* – Lie on your back, knee centred in coil\n3. \\*\\*Scan duration\\*\\* – 20–30 minutes\n4. \\*\\*Contrast injection\\*\\* (if ordered) – IV line, extra 5 minutes\n5. \\*\\*Completion\\*\\* – Return to change room; collect digital films & report link within 2 hours\n---\n## Caution Before the Test\n- \\*\\*Remove metallic items\\*\\* – Keys, coins, mobile phones\n- \\*\\*Disclose implants\\*\\* – Pacemakers, joint replacements, shrapnel\n- \\*\\*Claustrophobia?\\*\\* – Oral sedation or mild IV relaxant available"
